<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900711-0022</DOCNO><DOCID>900711-0022.</DOCID><HL>   International Brief -- All Nippon Airways:   Purchase of About 30 Jets   For $3.31 Billion Planned</HL><DATE>07/11/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A10</SO><CO>   J.ANA MD F.ABI</CO><IN>AEROSPACE (ARO)AIRLINES (AIR)</IN><LP>   All Nippon Airways of Japan will spend three monthsexamining four passenger airplanes and intends to purchaseabout 30 medium-sized jets for a total of 500 billion yen($3.31 billion), an official said.   The planes include the 767-X, a high-technology jet thatcan seat 407 people, being developed jointly by Japan and theU.S.; St. Louis-based McDonnell Douglas Corp.'s MD-11 with aseating capacity of 380; and the European consortium AirbusIndustrie's A-330, with a capacity of 385, and its A-340,seating 262 to 295.</LP><TEXT>   All Nippon, which operates 105 aircraft and is scheduledto receive a previous order for 20 more jets at year end, isone of several airlines shopping for a new generation ofwide-body aircraft to replace older McDonnell Douglas DC-10s,Lockheed Corp. L-1011s and Boeing 747s.   All Nippon will introduce the new planes over four to fiveyears starting in 1995, the official said. This is aimed atmeeting increasing passenger demand from three big airportconstruction projects in Japan planned for completion by themid-1990s.</TEXT></DOC>